body.p:
The yearly time series of cases spanning 1964–2019 was analyzed with autoregressive integrated moving average (ARIMA) models, which examined overall trends and periodicity. The autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation functions were used to select the model. The Dickey-Fuller test was used to study trends, and the Portmanteau test was used to study white noise from the residuals in the model. The 2010–2019 series was used to study the absolute and relative risk by locality. The Besag-York-Mollie (BYM) model was used to make Bayesian maps of relative risks to those expected by population size [16], using WinBUGS and ArcGIS software. The BYM model assumes that the number of cases (Oit) in area i and period t follows a Poisson distribution with the mean:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
